WEBVTT

00:03.522 --> 00:07.307
Each year, Gospel and Life offers a daily devotional during the season of Lent.

00:07.687 --> 00:10.230
The 40 days from Ash Wednesday through Good Friday.

00:10.671 --> 00:15.337
You can sign up to receive these daily devotionals by email at gospelandlife.com.

00:15.557 --> 00:17.660
That's gospelandlife.com.

00:18.180 --> 00:20.964
Now here's Dr. Keller with today's teaching.

00:28.073 --> 00:29.194
First Peter 110.

00:30.636 --> 00:32.338
Concerning this salvation,

00:33.602 --> 00:52.165
the prophets who spoke of the grace that was to come to you, searched intently and with the greatest care, trying to find out the time and the circumstances to which the Spirit of Christ in them was pointing when he predicted the sufferings of Christ and the glories that would follow.

00:53.006 --> 00:56.470
It was revealed to them that they were not serving themselves but you.

00:56.510 --> 01:03.058
When they spoke of the things that have now been told you by those who have preached the gospel to you,

01:03.170 --> 01:14.022
by the Holy Spirit sent from heaven into which things, even angels, long to look."

01:14.042 --> 01:14.883
This is God's Word.

01:14.923 --> 01:32.402
We're looking this year at this first epistle, this first letter of Peter, and we see that the theme of the book is on suffering and how to handle troubles and suffering.

01:32.898 --> 01:39.087
The book was written, as we saw, to people who were experiencing troubles and persecution.

01:40.228 --> 01:45.596
And the theme of the book is, just as Jesus Christ's sufferings led to glory.

01:45.796 --> 01:47.819
See, we read it right here in this passage already.

01:48.260 --> 02:01.458
Just as Jesus Christ's suffering led to glories that followed, your suffering and your troubles and your deepest distresses can be come

02:01.826 --> 02:08.894
Ways in which you become something great, not crushed, not small, not split, not broken, but something great.

02:09.875 --> 02:15.782
The sufferings that you go through can be like a furnace that turns your character and your heart into pure gold.

02:17.103 --> 02:19.025
That's what the text is about.

02:19.846 --> 02:30.578
We often sing that hymn that goes, I will always be with thee, thy troubles to bless and sanctify to thee.

02:30.754 --> 02:32.116
thy deepest distress.

02:32.557 --> 02:35.502
Sanctify to thee thy deepest distress.

02:35.542 --> 02:36.583
That's what the book's about.

02:37.124 --> 02:44.256
Now last week in verse 6, 7, 8, and 9, we actually looked at his first frontal treatment of this subject.

02:44.756 --> 02:58.258
And in that time, in verse 6, 7, 8, and 9, he actually showed how Christians have got something in their life that enables them to rejoice in the midst of the worst troubles.

02:59.330 --> 03:09.792
We saw that many people think that becoming a Christian means that now God protects us and keeps us from going through furnaces and going through troubles, but that's misguided.

03:10.413 --> 03:14.982
Rather, actually something much more brilliant and beautiful and poignant.

03:15.543 --> 03:17.988
Being a Christian does not mean you're exempt from sufferings.

03:18.028 --> 03:20.754
Being a Christian means that now you've got something in your life.

03:21.442 --> 03:23.365
that enables you to rise above those things.

03:23.625 --> 03:34.519
Yay, indeed, you've got something in your life that uses the sufferings and uses the troubles to actually make you something new.

03:35.360 --> 03:37.984
You know, back in the Middle Ages, there were the alchemists.

03:38.044 --> 03:40.046
What were the alchemists were going to do?

03:40.066 --> 03:44.812
They were trying to find that secret ingredient that would turn base metal into lead.

03:45.553 --> 03:49.138
Well, spiritually speaking, Peter says, Christians have found that.

03:50.818 --> 03:54.302
No matter what you are, this will turn you to gold when you go through sufferings.

03:54.342 --> 04:08.597
If you have it in your life, once was told by a friend of mine that if you put two gems into a gem tumbler, unless you put in the grinding compound, the gems might split each other.

04:08.617 --> 04:13.582
They might at least shatter each other or crack each other.

04:14.303 --> 04:17.266
So shivers would come off, but if you put in the grinding compound,

04:17.346 --> 04:21.631
that the contact between the gems would polish them, huh?

04:22.672 --> 04:24.334
So does the conflict polish you?

04:24.354 --> 04:27.717
Or does the conflict you're throwing into shatter you?

04:28.098 --> 04:29.940
It depends on whether that compound is in there.

04:30.781 --> 04:40.792
And Peter says there's something in a Christian's life that enables them, uses, actually, uses the suffering to turn them into something gold.

04:41.192 --> 04:42.994
Now, what is that?

04:43.875 --> 04:46.578
We haven't really talked much about it too much.

04:46.914 --> 04:49.557
And this week, suddenly, Peter moves into a new section.

04:50.158 --> 04:52.722
And he says, concerning this salvation.

04:52.782 --> 04:55.185
Now, what's his line of argument?

04:55.205 --> 04:55.826
What is he saying?

04:55.866 --> 04:57.668
How does this fit in with what we've seen so far?

04:58.029 --> 05:03.376
I think Peter is actually responding, like all good pastors, to an anticipated question.

05:03.396 --> 05:10.685
A good sermon, as you probably know, because you hear both good and bad ones here.

05:11.466 --> 05:14.290
When they're good, there's a dialogue going on.

05:14.626 --> 05:19.791
You listen to something, and then you start to say, but wait a minute, what in your heart?

05:19.811 --> 05:21.212
You say, but wait a minute, what about this?

05:21.332 --> 05:25.797
And Dargon, the sermon anticipates that, and it starts to answer that question.

05:26.517 --> 05:28.900
And then you think, but wait a minute, what about this?

05:28.960 --> 05:33.464
And then Dargon, the sermon anticipates the question again, and you feel like you've had a dialogue.

05:33.524 --> 05:39.129
Every real good sermon is a dialogue, and there's not a lot of them, and I don't give you a lot of them, but when I do, that's what happens.

05:39.550 --> 05:44.114
Now Peter is an inspired, authoritative,

05:44.706 --> 05:50.694
And so what he does when he is writing is he anticipates the questions, and I think he's anticipating this one.

05:52.256 --> 05:55.380
He is thinking, here's somebody saying, well, look, you know, I think I'm a Christian.

05:55.421 --> 05:55.861
I don't know.

05:55.881 --> 05:57.123
I guess I'm a Christian.

05:57.143 --> 06:05.174
I believe in Christianity, but I've been going through these deep distresses, and I'm going through these troubled waters, and I'm not rejoicing.

06:06.716 --> 06:14.226
So Peter says, well, concerning this salvation, and what he does in these three verses, and we're going to look at him for two weeks.

06:14.978 --> 06:24.770
What he does in these three verses is he says, I want you to know that it is important to continually get back to these basics of what it means to be saved.

06:24.830 --> 06:26.111
What it means to be a Christian.

06:26.532 --> 06:31.838
What the gospel is, the good news, the essential message of Christianity.

06:32.319 --> 06:41.650
He says, it's extremely important to know where to find and how to continually rehearse this, the salvation.

06:41.922 --> 06:43.443
this basic essential message.

06:43.804 --> 06:51.972
He makes this remarkable statement, which we will look at more next week, but at the very end of the passage, he says, into which things even angels long to look.

06:53.573 --> 07:00.240
He says, the basic essential, the basics of what it means to be a Christian is not something that you ever leave.

07:00.920 --> 07:04.023
You don't learn it once and then say, okay, now I understand that.

07:04.083 --> 07:05.344
I understand what it means to be a Christian.

07:05.385 --> 07:07.186
Now let me go on to more advanced things.

07:07.346 --> 07:07.747
Oh, no.

07:08.568 --> 07:11.090
He says, the basics of the gospel,

07:11.586 --> 07:13.808
are things into which angels long to look.

07:14.389 --> 07:15.570
How do you mean angels long to look?

07:15.650 --> 07:16.170
Oh, angels.

07:17.211 --> 07:19.554
It's a picturesque but profound statement.

07:21.295 --> 07:28.322
He says, if you ever think that you understand the gospel adequately, you are a small-minded person.

07:28.382 --> 07:30.484
I said, look at the angels, the perfect angels.

07:30.904 --> 07:41.234
They never tire of relooking, longing to look, gazing into, meditating on.

07:41.346 --> 07:46.231
penetrating more into this basic essential message of what is salvation?

07:46.411 --> 07:47.793
What does it mean to be saved?

07:48.274 --> 07:50.516
What does it mean to be a Christian?

07:50.956 --> 07:52.578
What is the gospel?

07:53.559 --> 07:55.822
What is the good news in the essential message?

07:55.842 --> 07:57.504
Angels never stop looking into that.

07:57.524 --> 07:57.964
Do you know that?

07:58.465 --> 07:59.586
They never get bored with it.

08:00.086 --> 08:02.949
They can't get bored with it because they know this is it.

08:02.969 --> 08:04.291
This is the ultimate truth.

08:05.012 --> 08:07.154
This is the most wonderful truth of all.

08:07.234 --> 08:18.487
And so what he actually does in verses 10, 11, and 12, he tells you what it is we're supposed to continually look into and how to do it, or where to do it.

08:18.968 --> 08:28.899
In other words, he gives us the basics of the salvation message, what it means to be a Christian, and then he tells us that you have to find it in the scripture, in the Old Testament prophets and in the New Testament apostles' teachings.

08:29.340 --> 08:32.924
So what we really have is two things we're gonna look at, and one this week and one next week.

08:33.485 --> 08:34.706
This week we're gonna look at

08:34.882 --> 08:48.195
What Peter says is the basic message of salvation because looking into that like the angels do, thinking about it and understanding it is the only way that you get through deep distresses.

08:48.255 --> 08:49.055
It's the only way.

08:49.356 --> 08:54.260
Holding on to this is the only way that you actually find going through deep distresses sanctifies you.

08:54.841 --> 08:57.183
The only way that going through furnaces purifies you.

08:58.585 --> 08:59.285
Hold on to this.

09:00.086 --> 09:03.029
And then the second thing he shows us is how you can look into it.

09:03.049 --> 09:04.370
You have to read the Bible.

09:04.674 --> 09:11.282
Now next week we'll look at what the Bible is, what does Peter say to us in this passage about the Bible, but this week we're really looking at the basics.

09:11.342 --> 09:17.771
I know that if you smart people who are looking at the schedule of sermons realize that I've just reversed the order.

09:17.931 --> 09:21.215
Well, my prerogative, I guess, I reversed the order.

09:21.555 --> 09:23.718
This week the basics next week, what is the scripture?

09:24.859 --> 09:30.066
And you know why we all need to know, if you don't believe Christianity,

09:31.298 --> 09:39.470
You need to know the basics because an awful lot of people who think they understand Christianity reject Christianity because they don't know what it really means.

09:39.550 --> 09:40.631
They don't really know what it is.

09:42.033 --> 09:56.454
But those of us who say, oh, I'm a believer, we need to understand the basics because if we don't long to look into it and learn to look into it like the angels do, we're never going to have lives of joy and power and death.

09:56.514 --> 09:59.058
We're, you know, here at verse eight,

09:59.554 --> 10:01.336
This is something we read last week.

10:01.877 --> 10:09.886
In verse eight, Paul says, Peter says, though you do not see him, you love him and you can handle all your sufferings.

10:09.946 --> 10:10.146
Why?

10:10.226 --> 10:16.193
Because though you do not see him, you believe in him and are filled with joy unspeakable and full of glory.

10:18.195 --> 10:26.464
Could you truly and honestly describe yesterday's quiet time, your devotional with those words?

10:26.965 --> 10:27.986
Yes, I had a,

10:28.194 --> 10:35.208
I sat down and I read the Bible and I prayed and I spent some time with God and I experienced joy, unspeakable and full of glory.

10:35.228 --> 10:37.473
And is that a fair way to sum up your week?

10:39.276 --> 10:40.298
Is it a fair way to do it?

10:40.478 --> 10:40.979
Why not?

10:42.322 --> 10:45.008
You know, how can Peter say to a group of people, he's writing a church.

10:45.929 --> 10:48.274
He's writing a church and he assumes.

10:48.898 --> 10:51.262
that they're experiencing joy unspeakable and full of glory.

10:51.282 --> 10:56.712
He doesn't say you might be, some of you might be, you most mature people, you elders, you know, the pastors, I'm sure.

10:56.932 --> 11:00.619
Some of you more advanced Christians are probably experiencing joy unspeakable and full of glory.

11:00.659 --> 11:02.582
No, he says, you, all of you.

11:04.606 --> 11:05.247
How could that be?

11:05.307 --> 11:11.538
Because they're looking, they're looking, they're looking at the basic gospel.

11:12.162 --> 11:13.684
They're longing to look into it.

11:13.744 --> 11:14.606
Now, here's what it is.

11:14.706 --> 11:15.327
Let's take a look.

11:15.887 --> 11:17.189
One of the things that's so interesting.

11:17.510 --> 11:18.992
What is the gospel this week next week?

11:19.032 --> 11:19.753
How do you find it?

11:19.773 --> 11:22.216
How do you read it and look into it by reading the Scripture?

11:24.980 --> 11:27.424
Typical views of what it means to be a Christian.

11:27.764 --> 11:32.531
The intellectual view says basically being a Christian is someone who subscribes to a certain set of views.

11:32.872 --> 11:37.218
If you sign on your Christian, when people tell me, I've always believed.

11:37.859 --> 11:38.760
I've always been a Christian.

11:38.780 --> 11:39.922
I've always believed.

11:40.386 --> 11:49.457
Usually, not always, but usually that means that there's been a certain set of beliefs that I was raised with and I've never given them up.

11:49.478 --> 11:51.300
That's the intellectual view of Christianity.

11:51.320 --> 11:52.621
It's basically a cognitive thing.

11:52.642 --> 11:55.705
You sign the statements of beliefs and you're Christian.

11:56.526 --> 12:00.031
A second view, of course, is not the intellectual view, it's the behavioral view.

12:00.111 --> 12:02.514
I'll be real quick on this because we often rehearse these.

12:03.074 --> 12:05.298
The behavioral view is, ah, doctrine doesn't matter.

12:05.358 --> 12:16.656
What a Christian really is is a good person, a person who loves his or her neighbor, a person who works for the good of humankind, a person who lives after the example of Christ.

12:16.696 --> 12:18.499
What he or she believes isn't as important.

12:18.519 --> 12:21.263
Doctrine, the cognitive is an important, it's the behavioral.

12:21.804 --> 12:23.507
And then there's a third way to look at it.

12:23.527 --> 12:27.554
And some people talk about Christianity as a kind of mystical experience.

12:27.954 --> 12:30.258
Ah, they say to be a Christian.

12:30.434 --> 12:32.756
means you actually have to have an encounter with God.

12:32.796 --> 12:37.661
You have to have an encounter with the infinite, and you must have felt something.

12:37.681 --> 12:42.466
You must have felt that there's been some encounter and that your life has been changed in some way.

12:42.746 --> 12:47.291
It's not something you can define, and you certainly can't push it on other people, but there it is.

12:47.371 --> 12:52.436
It's a mystical experience, a personal, deep, profound experience.

12:53.317 --> 12:58.642
If what Peter says here, the gospel is, if what Peter says here is true,

12:59.170 --> 13:01.394
None of those views is really big enough.

13:04.078 --> 13:10.328
Peter summarizes the salvation with a single phrase that all I want to do is pull it apart for the next few minutes.

13:11.550 --> 13:15.796
It's a beautiful, beautiful summary of what it means to become a Christian of what the gospel is.

13:15.917 --> 13:23.889
One of the great things about the Bible is that there is no one canned description of the gospel.

13:24.430 --> 13:26.994
There's just hundreds of them.

13:27.458 --> 13:32.425
dozens and scores and hundreds of summaries, each one of which shows you something new.

13:32.445 --> 13:33.046
Here's what he says.

13:33.146 --> 13:41.339
Concerning this salvation, look at verse 10, the prophet spoke to you of the grace that was to come to you, and then he goes on.

13:42.500 --> 13:43.402
There's a synonym here.

13:44.383 --> 13:45.525
What is the salvation?

13:46.006 --> 13:48.650
How does he describe the salvation, this basic gospel?

13:49.511 --> 13:50.673
What does it mean to be a Christian?

13:50.733 --> 13:51.854
These are all the same questions.

13:53.136 --> 13:53.537
Here it is.

13:55.319 --> 13:57.042
The grace has come to you.

13:57.890 --> 14:01.094
What does it mean to be a Christian to have the grace of God come to you?

14:02.216 --> 14:02.997
Has that happened to you?

14:04.419 --> 14:05.961
Do you understand what that means?

14:06.121 --> 14:07.182
Here, let me break it down.

14:07.663 --> 14:11.208
First of all, to be a Christian means to have God come to you.

14:12.950 --> 14:25.266
To be a Christian, obviously at this point shows that the initiative, let's break this down even, to be a Christian means that you understand that the initiative is with God.

14:26.562 --> 14:31.228
It's not talking about, it never starts, the gospel never starts with what you do.

14:31.248 --> 14:34.152
It always starts with what God has done.

14:34.412 --> 14:35.573
God has broken in.

14:35.914 --> 14:37.656
God has done something momentous.

14:38.056 --> 14:39.118
God is on the way.

14:39.538 --> 14:40.700
God has broken through.

14:40.740 --> 14:45.506
Now, what I'm about to say is not a criticism of other religions.

14:45.586 --> 14:49.631
It's a simple, it's a simple distinction, a simple fact.

14:50.392 --> 14:51.954
And nobody would disagree with this.

14:52.802 --> 14:55.666
Right here we see when it says that, you know, what is salvation?

14:55.747 --> 15:02.077
That God has come to you, shows how different Christian salvation is from the concept of salvation in any of the religion.

15:02.738 --> 15:07.305
Every other religion is basically a philosophy, it's basically a teaching.

15:08.987 --> 15:16.459
But Christianity is the report of an event, something God has done, very different.

15:16.780 --> 15:20.946
See, Buddhism is a philosophy, a way of looking at life.

15:21.666 --> 15:30.379
If you read the Buddha scriptures, there's a lot of discussion about who Buddha was and what he did and what stories he told and where he went and where he was born and where he lived.

15:30.980 --> 15:31.881
But here's what's interesting.

15:32.883 --> 15:37.870
We don't have no idea whether or not the things that the Buddha scriptures tell about Buddha are true.

15:37.970 --> 15:39.953
We don't know if he really was born in this time.

15:39.974 --> 15:41.396
We don't really know if he lived in this time.

15:41.416 --> 15:43.178
We don't know if that was his mother's or father's name.

15:43.739 --> 15:46.924
And it makes no difference to Buddhism, whether it's true or not.

15:47.144 --> 15:48.306
No difference at all.

15:48.706 --> 15:51.589
because Buddhism is a philosophy of teaching that you pick up.

15:52.470 --> 15:55.534
It's a teaching that you pick up and you decide, I'm going to do it.

15:56.395 --> 16:00.559
So it starts with you receiving this teaching and doing something about it.

16:01.720 --> 16:02.742
Same thing with Mohammed.

16:04.163 --> 16:17.458
There's a lot of things that the Quran says about Mohammed's life, and I'm not trying to insult anybody here who might be a Muslim by saying, and it's fair, perfectly fair to say, your Islamic faith does not depend

16:18.274 --> 16:20.898
on whether Mohammed did this or this or this or this.

16:21.439 --> 16:33.117
Oh yes, of course, one of the reasons why we go to Mecca is because that's where he was from and one of the reasons why this and that has been observed in the Muslim faith is because we're remembering what the prophet did.

16:33.438 --> 16:46.578
But the point is there is nothing actually in the way in which the Islamic faith is carried out in a day-to-day basis that actually depends on whether or not Mohammed really lived or died or did any of those things.

16:47.042 --> 16:50.085
Because every other religion says, it starts with you.

16:50.346 --> 16:51.667
It's a teaching, it's a philosophy.

16:52.128 --> 16:54.250
Christianity, the Christian gospel is not that.

16:54.710 --> 17:00.857
If you want the gospel, you don't go to the Ten Commandments, you don't go to the Sermon on the Mount.

17:00.877 --> 17:03.179
Christianity has teaching, but it is not a teaching.

17:03.320 --> 17:06.423
In essence, it's a report of something God has done.

17:06.803 --> 17:07.644
God is on the way.

17:07.945 --> 17:08.806
God has broken through.

17:09.046 --> 17:09.927
God has done something.

17:10.227 --> 17:16.594
Therefore, Christianity never starts with you, starts with God, and never starts with what you must do, but starts with what God has done.

17:17.026 --> 17:21.511
It never starts by saying, do this or experience this or even believe this.

17:23.293 --> 17:33.105
You know, Christianity does not start saying we have to believe because frankly, if God hadn't done what the gospel says he's done, all the believing in the world won't help you a bit.

17:33.585 --> 17:35.828
All the faith you work up won't make a bit of difference.

17:37.270 --> 17:39.773
The gospel is God has come.

17:39.813 --> 17:40.774
He's broken in.

17:40.834 --> 17:42.115
He has done something.

17:42.596 --> 17:44.338
Jesus Christ, who was God,

17:44.962 --> 17:53.075
breaks into history, and he is born, and he lives, and he dies, and he's risen again, all for you, if you believe in him.

17:53.575 --> 17:55.478
That's a report of something God has done.

17:55.518 --> 17:56.440
Now here's what it means.

17:56.480 --> 17:57.341
Let me put it this way.

17:58.243 --> 18:00.105
This is what it means to be a Christian.

18:00.486 --> 18:05.133
This is what it means to understand the gospel, and this is what it means to have your life controlled by the gospel.

18:05.534 --> 18:06.155
It means this.

18:07.076 --> 18:13.426
It means that the controlling factor, if you're a Christian, the controlling factor in your

18:13.538 --> 18:27.607
relationship to God, your relationship to the world, your relationship to yourself, the controlling factor, your relationship to God, the world and the self is not what you have done or what you are doing, but what Jesus Christ has done.

18:29.872 --> 18:32.658
The controlling factor in everything

18:33.218 --> 18:37.543
is not what you have done but what he has done because the gospel is it starts with what God has done.

18:37.664 --> 18:38.985
God has done something momentous.

18:39.346 --> 18:41.128
God has done something universe splitting.

18:41.388 --> 18:43.231
God has done something world shattering.

18:43.471 --> 18:48.617
He sent his son and he lived, he died, he paid the penalty verse and Jesus has done something.

18:48.697 --> 18:49.559
God has done something.

18:49.879 --> 18:54.725
This means at every point, what does it mean to be controlled by this gospel?

18:54.765 --> 18:56.267
This is essential basic.

18:56.327 --> 18:59.872
It means how do you know God will answer your prayer?

19:00.572 --> 19:01.874
How do you deal with criticism?

19:02.306 --> 19:03.547
How do you think about yourself?

19:03.868 --> 19:05.109
How do you decide who you are?

19:05.810 --> 19:10.895
At every juncture, you can either look first to your performance or first to Jesus' performance.

19:11.395 --> 19:12.016
It's up to you.

19:12.997 --> 19:14.198
Are you gonna go the way of the gospel?

19:14.218 --> 19:19.504
You're gonna go the way of every other religion, every other philosophy that says, you start by picking up the teaching.

19:19.784 --> 19:23.327
You start by believing, you start by obeying, you start by doing.

19:23.388 --> 19:24.689
That's how you're saved.

19:24.909 --> 19:26.010
No, the gospel says.

19:26.791 --> 19:29.714
The Christian gospel says it starts by saying, God has done something.

19:31.586 --> 19:32.988
So you can be controlled.

19:33.028 --> 19:38.237
You can decide the controlling factor in my relationship with God is my performance, what I've done or what Jesus has done.

19:40.060 --> 19:42.544
Some of you really need to know that tonight in particular.

19:45.830 --> 19:49.816
You say, I'd like to pray, but why should God listen to me after what's happened?

19:51.359 --> 19:54.003
What is the controlling factor in your relationship with God now?

19:55.446 --> 19:57.970
What you have done or what he has done?

19:59.298 --> 20:03.763
grace of God comes to you, it's come through, it's broken through, it's what's he's done.

20:03.783 --> 20:06.646
That's the thing that should control everything.

20:06.666 --> 20:09.509
When you think about how do you react how people are treating you?

20:09.569 --> 20:12.132
How do you face the future?

20:13.233 --> 20:14.315
How do you face the future?

20:14.815 --> 20:18.199
You can either look at your record, you can look at what you've done, you can look at what Jesus has done.

20:18.339 --> 20:19.580
One or the other, what are you gonna do?

20:19.741 --> 20:20.461
It's up to you now.

20:23.064 --> 20:26.788
And so I see the first thing we understand when it comes to, what does it mean to be a Christian?

20:26.928 --> 20:28.370
A Christian means

20:28.642 --> 20:32.847
To be a Christian means to see that everything starts with God, something that he's done.

20:33.788 --> 20:40.155
The gospel is actually a report that God has done something momentous and world-shattering.

20:40.175 --> 20:40.775
Don't you see?

20:42.277 --> 20:44.640
Christianity is not just intellectual, it's not just volitional.

20:44.900 --> 20:45.561
Here's the test.

20:45.921 --> 20:53.970
Until you recognize the magnitude, the overwhelming character of the report of the gospel,

20:54.114 --> 20:59.522
that will fill you up volitionally, intellectually, emotionally, mystically, and in every other way.

21:01.365 --> 21:03.188
Being a Christian is multi-dimensional.

21:03.248 --> 21:04.129
It's comprehensive.

21:04.149 --> 21:05.311
It affects everything.

21:06.653 --> 21:20.434
So when we say a Christian is someone whose had God come to you, first of all, we mean a Christian is someone who understands that your relationship to God rests totally on what his initiative, his coming,

21:21.954 --> 21:24.899
Why is there so much pain and suffering in the world?

21:25.360 --> 21:31.290
And how do we handle it in a way that won't destroy us, but could actually make us stronger, wiser, and more hopeful?

21:32.012 --> 21:41.468
All month long on Gospel and Life, Tim Keller is teaching from the book of 1 Peter, and looking at how Peter encouraged early believers who were facing intense suffering and pain.

21:42.169 --> 21:44.754
In his book Walking with God Through Pain and Suffering,

21:44.802 --> 21:52.669
Dr. Keller takes a deeper look at how, with God's help, we can face life's most intense challenges and confront the hard questions on suffering.

21:53.229 --> 21:59.475
Through deep pastoral insight and real life stories, Dr. Keller explores how we can face pain and suffering in our own lives.

22:00.015 --> 22:09.503
This month, walking with God through pain and suffering is our thank you for your gift to help Gospel and Life share the message of Christ's love and compassion with people all over the world.

22:10.024 --> 22:14.788
So request your copy today at gospelandlife.com.

22:14.768 --> 22:19.614
Now, here's Dr. Keller with the remainder of today's teaching.

22:22.677 --> 22:23.779
But not only that, look.

22:24.740 --> 22:30.326
Another way to understand this, a Christian is somebody who's had God come in.

22:32.349 --> 22:36.554
You see, this salvation is the grace of God comes to you.

22:37.134 --> 22:43.602
Now, what I mean by that is if you're a Christian, sooner or later you will be aware that there is a foreign power

22:44.450 --> 22:45.412
that has invaded you.

22:47.055 --> 22:48.658
This is very, very important.

22:48.838 --> 22:52.345
Again, here's the difference between Christianity and what you might call mere religion.

22:54.188 --> 22:59.798
You know, in the last couple of weeks, I've talked about this, and so people might get a wrong impression.

22:59.818 --> 23:08.274
I've said that people, human beings, are inveterately, are incarnatively religious, and there's more and more

23:08.450 --> 23:20.646
is more and more articles you're gonna see, there's more and more people coming out and saying that we thought this 20th century was going to be a century in which human beings and civilization got less and less religious, and now we found out we were wrong.

23:21.307 --> 23:27.055
Religion is more of a factor, as much of a factor in human history and in human affairs as it has ever been.

23:27.075 --> 23:31.180
And therefore, now everybody's saying, look how religious we are.

23:31.301 --> 23:35.346
Everyone, everyone, is got a sense of God.

23:35.970 --> 23:41.639
Everyone has got all cultures and all races and all societies, they're just so religious.

23:42.420 --> 23:44.283
Yes, of course I've said that, of course that's true.

23:45.365 --> 24:04.114
But the Bible is careful to say, especially in the book of Romans, that whereas every human being needs God, and in that sense every human being desires God, the Bible insists that every human being refuses to seek the true God

24:05.954 --> 24:22.274
In Romans 1, it says, because we do not want to lose our sovereignty, and we don't want to lose control of our lives, the way in which we respond to this need for God on the inside is we create gods of our own choosing.

24:22.754 --> 24:24.056
We fashion gods.

24:24.116 --> 24:25.197
We create religions.

24:25.217 --> 24:35.730
The Bible says that all of the natural religious impulse of human beings is oriented and is intended to get away from the real God.

24:37.154 --> 24:47.650
And if you look at all the different religions that rise out of your heart, they always move toward a God of some sort, but the Bible says, toward the real God, no.

24:48.731 --> 24:56.623
And therefore, you must never think that Christianity really is the natural searching of your heart for God.

24:57.164 --> 25:00.108
And you're going out looking for Him, and you're going out seeking Him.

25:00.569 --> 25:04.295
And Christianity means people who are seeking God find Him.

25:04.535 --> 25:05.757
That's not the gospel at all.

25:05.777 --> 25:06.578
It doesn't say that.

25:08.162 --> 25:21.716
A Christian is somebody who realizes that you may have been religious, you may not have been religious, you may have been wildly religious, but a Christian is somebody who finds that at some point in your life a foreign power, God, something from the outside has come in and begun to deal with you.

25:22.777 --> 25:23.998
It's begun to shake you up.

25:24.979 --> 25:26.440
It's begun to change your life.

25:27.621 --> 25:36.210
And that is the big difference between someone who is a Christian who understands the gospel and someone who's just simply seeking

25:36.386 --> 25:38.148
seeking in a general way for God.

25:38.168 --> 25:40.390
The Bible says no one seeks the true God.

25:41.071 --> 25:42.172
You might seek something.

25:42.192 --> 25:44.115
You might seek spirituality.

25:44.135 --> 25:45.817
You might seek spiritual fulfillment.

25:46.257 --> 25:49.300
You might seek religious experience.

25:49.340 --> 25:52.324
But the Bible says you won't seek the real God unless he himself comes to you.

25:52.924 --> 25:55.647
And when that happens, you feel disturbed.

25:56.889 --> 26:00.513
The way you know you're a Christian is something is bringing you up short.

26:02.936 --> 26:05.138
See, whenever I talk to people,

26:05.826 --> 26:14.437
who seem to be very, very upset, very angry sometimes, struggling and trying to understand Christianity in the gospel.

26:14.477 --> 26:16.179
Sometimes I get a lot of hope when I see that.

26:16.520 --> 26:18.422
I have more hope for them than I do very often.

26:18.622 --> 26:21.065
The smug person who says, well, of course I'm a Christian.

26:21.085 --> 26:21.886
I've always gone to church.

26:21.906 --> 26:22.367
You know why?

26:22.387 --> 26:24.650
The person who says, of course I'm a Christian.

26:24.670 --> 26:25.451
I've always gone to church.

26:26.592 --> 26:34.162
It worries me because that person doesn't seem to give me the indication that there was ever a time in which God invaded.

26:35.618 --> 26:37.521
The grace of God comes to you, comes from outside.

26:37.541 --> 26:38.262
There's an invasion.

26:38.342 --> 26:39.824
Invasions are always traumatic.

26:40.404 --> 26:41.506
You know what the poet says.

26:41.566 --> 26:43.268
There's an old poet that put it this way.

26:44.690 --> 26:50.017
I have been disturbed with the joys of elevated thought.

26:50.238 --> 26:50.698
You heard that?

26:51.840 --> 26:55.685
A Christian is somebody who's deeply disturbed.

26:55.705 --> 26:56.726
A Christian is somebody.

26:56.766 --> 26:59.410
Things are not going the way you expected.

27:00.071 --> 27:02.514
Things are not going the way you wanted them to go.

27:02.978 --> 27:07.525
There's a sense in which God is coming to you and dealing with you and you might be upset about it.

27:07.565 --> 27:11.150
For a long time, even before you ever even admit that you believe, you might be aggravated.

27:11.170 --> 27:14.495
You might wish that you could go back to the time in which you hadn't even heard about God.

27:15.036 --> 27:19.422
You might wish that you weren't bothered by these ideas and these thoughts and these wrestling.

27:19.442 --> 27:20.864
So that's a good sign.

27:22.567 --> 27:27.634
What it means to be a Christian is to have the grace of God come from the outside.

27:29.218 --> 27:30.699
It comes in and it deals with you.

27:30.719 --> 27:32.641
You feel that something is gotta hold of you.

27:32.681 --> 27:33.682
Something is grabbing you.

27:34.043 --> 27:34.443
What is it?

27:36.185 --> 27:39.268
It's your creator, the one who made you, making you again.

27:39.308 --> 27:41.670
And that's a very traumatic experience.

27:41.690 --> 27:42.571
Has that happened to you?

27:42.591 --> 27:46.014
Okay, and now we're moving on through.

27:47.696 --> 27:48.677
What does it mean to be a Christian?

27:48.737 --> 27:55.343
Number one, to see that something God has done is the controlling factor in your life now.

27:56.324 --> 27:58.546
Jesus' performance, something that he has done,

27:59.458 --> 28:01.944
Christianity starts not with what you do, but what he's done.

28:01.984 --> 28:02.907
It's a report of an event.

28:02.947 --> 28:06.255
Secondly, a Christian is somebody who's been invaded from the outside.

28:07.177 --> 28:10.746
God has come on in and be going to shake you up and started to move you around in that way.

28:11.067 --> 28:11.909
Has that happened to you?

28:13.233 --> 28:14.376
You might get hostile.

28:14.436 --> 28:15.378
That's a good sign.

28:16.514 --> 28:17.835
You might feel disturbed.

28:17.855 --> 28:18.556
That's a good sign.

28:18.776 --> 28:28.345
But I'll tell you something, if you are smug, if you are placid, if nothing seems to be out of the ordinary, if you're Christianity has always been kind of like a smooth flowing river.

28:28.686 --> 28:30.407
Yes, I've always been Christian.

28:30.728 --> 28:32.349
I've always come to church.

28:32.609 --> 28:33.610
I've always believed these things.

28:33.630 --> 28:34.651
I've always tried my best.

28:34.911 --> 28:38.395
And there's never been a time in which you can say the grace of God came.

28:38.955 --> 28:39.556
It invaded.

28:39.596 --> 28:46.002
Invasions are never sweet.

28:46.402 --> 28:47.564
They're never placid.

28:48.004 --> 28:49.066
They're never a joy.

28:49.707 --> 28:51.409
They tend to be traumatic.

28:51.970 --> 28:53.472
And that's what it means to be a Christian.

28:53.912 --> 29:04.627
Now, not only that, the third and last thing, to be a Christian means to see these other two things, but now to be a Christian is to receive and understand the grace of God.

29:05.148 --> 29:15.602
See what amazes me and also what excites me is that Peter is able to take salvation and boil it down into one word.

29:16.322 --> 29:21.892
You know, in the first few verses of 1 Peter, there was an awful lot of wonderful words that he talked about.

29:21.932 --> 29:24.416
He said, we're going to have a salvation in the future.

29:24.456 --> 29:36.597
We have pardon of our sins, and we have God's keeping power, and we have the sprinkled blood of Jesus on us, and we have the sanctifying of the Spirit.

29:36.617 --> 29:41.906
There's this whole array of wonderful powers and privileges that all come in under the heading of salvation.

29:42.210 --> 29:44.653
Here, Peter is able to boil it all down into one word.

29:45.013 --> 29:48.637
He's able to say, everything comes down to one thing, grace.

29:49.799 --> 29:51.441
Everything comes down to one thing, grace.

29:53.603 --> 30:02.433
And a Christian is somebody who understands grace, who receives grace, who sees that everything God has done toward you is all of grace.

30:02.453 --> 30:04.576
And let me put it in the worst possible way.

30:04.616 --> 30:06.418
There's always a negative and a positive here.

30:08.194 --> 30:18.790
If it's really true that Peter can say everything God has done, and he can summon all up and say it's all grace, that means that there is nothing that God has done that he owes you.

30:19.911 --> 30:21.153
You don't deserve any of it.

30:22.114 --> 30:23.837
See, there's a negative sign to everything.

30:24.899 --> 30:27.542
When Peter says, everything God does to you is grace.

30:27.562 --> 30:31.268
Before you say, oh, everything God, what that means is he don't deserve a thing.

30:33.111 --> 30:35.474
Because in the Bible, the word grace means

30:35.682 --> 30:36.804
unmerited favor.

30:36.864 --> 30:39.287
You may have heard that before, but let me push it to you a little further.

30:39.748 --> 30:40.970
Let me push it down a little further.

30:41.010 --> 30:47.239
Grace does not mean giving something, giving favor to somebody to whom you simply owe nothing.

30:49.021 --> 30:54.409
Grace always means showing favor to someone to whom you owe the opposite.

30:56.412 --> 31:03.442
Do not think grace means like you're walking on by and here's a homeless person who says, could I have some money and you put some money in the cup.

31:04.194 --> 31:05.536
You don't know that person anything.

31:05.916 --> 31:06.758
You put money in the cup.

31:06.798 --> 31:07.378
Is that grace?

31:08.720 --> 31:12.305
Not according to the scripture, at least not this kind of deep grace.

31:12.325 --> 31:13.647
Let me tell you what grace is more like.

31:15.710 --> 31:26.585
Someone who has been kicking you, someone who has been ripping you off, someone who has been dishonest to you, someone who has been mean to you, and that person suddenly is in need.

31:27.146 --> 31:32.914
And you come in with not only enough money and enough help to meet the need, but more.

31:33.506 --> 31:34.748
than that person really needs.

31:35.308 --> 31:36.189
That's grace.

31:37.070 --> 31:39.313
And you say, how could that, what?

31:40.074 --> 31:44.580
The grace, real grace, is always, therefore, counterintuitive.

31:45.581 --> 31:47.784
Why do you think John Newton wrote to him the way he did it?

31:48.224 --> 31:51.248
Real grace is always amazing, always, it's always shocking.

31:51.949 --> 31:56.194
It's not shocking to see somebody put money in the cup of a homeless person.

31:56.535 --> 31:59.218
It's free, in a sense, it's unobligated, yes.

31:59.458 --> 32:00.660
We're not talking about that.

32:00.720 --> 32:04.546
When the Bible talks about grace is talking about something, always that is absolutely shocking.

32:05.328 --> 32:06.389
In fact, we'll put it this way.

32:06.870 --> 32:09.855
Real grace, and here's how you can tell whether you've experienced the grace of God or not.

32:09.895 --> 32:17.307
Real grace is shocking, counterintuitive, amazing, shocking, and threatening.

32:20.212 --> 32:21.714
It's shocking and threatening.

32:22.754 --> 32:26.920
Let me give you an example that I've used before, but actually I have new insight and I had to share it with you.

32:28.041 --> 32:35.551
Most of us who have lived in New York for a long time find out that you end up going to certain Broadway plays a lot because it all depends on who's coming to see you.

32:36.593 --> 32:46.546
At least once a year, you go to see the same, at least once a year I go to see Les Mis, because somebody comes to town.

32:47.234 --> 32:52.626
I've used this illustration before, but it was always an imperfection about it, I thought, until the last time I went.

32:53.728 --> 32:59.200
If you want a wonderful illustration of Grace, I always thought, you go to the beginning of the play, or the beginning of the book.

32:59.220 --> 33:01.445
And here you have Jean Valjean, who's a criminal.

33:01.865 --> 33:03.028
He's an ex-convict now.

33:03.950 --> 33:05.874
And he's taken into the Bishop's house.

33:06.466 --> 33:17.759
And when the bishop is gone, he steals a lot of his valuables and he runs away and the police catch him and they bring him back and they throw him down in front of the bishop and says, we caught this criminal with your goods.

33:18.179 --> 33:20.402
And the bishop looks at him and says, oh, that's not true.

33:20.462 --> 33:21.523
I gave him all those things.

33:21.563 --> 33:28.411
And by the way, my dear friend, you forgot something and he grabs the candlesticks and he puts them in his hands and says, don't forget, I gave you the candlesticks too.

33:29.913 --> 33:30.834
Now, you know,

33:31.234 --> 33:36.782
That's a great, I used to think a great illustration of grace, but maybe not so great because I said the trouble was he lied.

33:36.822 --> 33:38.604
He lied to the police.

33:40.146 --> 33:45.354
Last time I used the illustration in a service, I probably didn't mention that because it kind of hurts it, doesn't it?

33:45.394 --> 33:45.934
Yeah, he lied.

33:46.075 --> 33:47.817
How good an illustration is of that?

33:47.837 --> 33:55.688
Then I began to realize, see the last time I went and I watched it, I realized, oh my gosh, it's even a better illustration than I thought of what Jesus did for us.

33:56.910 --> 33:58.672
I realized that it wasn't a lie at all.

33:59.353 --> 34:00.114
You know why?

34:00.898 --> 34:05.744
Because the bishop, when he took this ex-convict in, he knew what this man was capable of.

34:06.445 --> 34:08.027
He knew it was in the man's heart.

34:08.487 --> 34:13.854
And when he took the guy in, he put everything at risk.

34:13.874 --> 34:15.376
And so in a sense, he gave it all away.

34:16.657 --> 34:20.061
Because you see, real grace is shocking.

34:21.283 --> 34:23.986
The bishop, by bringing the man in,

34:25.634 --> 34:30.279
opened himself, made himself vulnerable, made himself weak, and allowed himself to be plundered.

34:30.459 --> 34:32.562
And so the fact is that it wasn't a lie.

34:33.363 --> 34:40.911
By even the act of taking in the ex-convict, the bishop had actually been saying, I know what you're capable of, and it's all right.

34:41.612 --> 34:43.174
I'm going to serve you even if you do that.

34:43.274 --> 34:43.935
It really was.

34:43.995 --> 34:45.256
He'd given it all away.

34:45.296 --> 34:51.744
And in the same way, if you want to understand Jesus Christ to you, it's just as shocking.

34:52.144 --> 34:53.746
Jesus Christ made himself weak.

34:54.210 --> 34:56.132
Jesus Christ made himself vulnerable.

34:56.172 --> 34:56.933
He came to earth.

34:56.953 --> 35:02.019
He put himself in the hands of people who hate the idea of somebody telling them how to live.

35:03.120 --> 35:05.082
So he came to the very people he was going to save.

35:05.443 --> 35:06.764
He let himself be plundered.

35:07.665 --> 35:13.992
Grace is shocking, but, and here's the way you can tell that you've really experienced the grace of God.

35:14.312 --> 35:15.053
It's threatening.

35:17.896 --> 35:22.962
In the novel, they miss, Victor Hugo has this wonderful, wonderful line.

35:23.778 --> 35:31.729
As soon as the bishop showed Jean-Vell John this grace, incredible grace, shocking grace, real grace.

35:32.490 --> 35:38.598
A grace that really was modeled on Christ's grace because he didn't just give favor to someone who to whom he owed nothing.

35:39.099 --> 35:42.404
He gave grace, he gave favor to someone to whom he owed the opposite.

35:43.265 --> 35:45.748
He gave softness to someone who deserved toughness.

35:47.651 --> 35:52.818
He gave openness to someone who deserved closeness.

35:53.858 --> 36:05.296
And the great line, when it happened, Victor Hugo says about Jean Valjean, he says, Jean Valjean could not say if he had been touched or humiliated.

36:06.638 --> 36:10.304
Now let me tell you, if you ever start to experience the grace of God, you feel the same way.

36:10.344 --> 36:14.130
When God starts to open your heart, when he starts to tell you how much he loves you,

36:15.554 --> 36:16.356
Here's how you know.

36:16.776 --> 36:18.460
You're experiencing understanding the grace of God.

36:18.480 --> 36:19.542
You will always feel the same way.

36:19.582 --> 36:21.766
You have no idea whether you should feel good or bad.

36:22.027 --> 36:22.608
You feel both.

36:22.969 --> 36:24.833
You feel touched and absolutely humiliated.

36:24.853 --> 36:26.416
Listen, he goes on.

36:26.476 --> 36:28.620
He says, he didn't know if he was touched or humiliated.

36:28.941 --> 36:32.829
In opposition to this celestial kindness, he summoned up his pride.

36:32.929 --> 36:37.458
The priest's pardon was the most formidable act hack he had ever sustained.

36:38.466 --> 36:42.413
He felt his hardness of heart would be complete if he could resist this kind as that.

36:42.873 --> 36:49.965
If he yielded to it, he would have to renounce the hatred with which his mistreatment by others had filled his soul and in which he'd found satisfaction.

36:50.847 --> 36:54.473
In the face of this assault, he knew he had to conquer or be conquered.

36:55.074 --> 36:55.294
See?

36:56.716 --> 37:02.546
It's one thing to get grace from somebody who owes you nothing, but when you get grace from somebody who owes you the opposite,

37:04.578 --> 37:09.944
you realize your debt to that person is so deep that you will never be able to pay it back.

37:09.984 --> 37:11.926
You realize it goes beyond the accounting.

37:11.966 --> 37:14.588
You realize the numbers are too big now.

37:15.069 --> 37:16.030
I'll never pay it off.

37:16.270 --> 37:17.471
It goes beyond reckoning.

37:17.511 --> 37:31.506
And that means that when you receive grace from somebody who owes you the opposite, who owes you opposition, hostility, litigation, and you know, this person is going to give me

37:31.842 --> 37:44.158
grace and favor, it threatens you because you realize you will lose your sovereignty, you will lose control, you will never pay that person back, you will owe that person your life for the rest of your life, and therefore grace always scares you.

37:44.218 --> 37:51.347
And the grace of God when it comes in will either turn you into a more hard person than ever or break your heart into eternal softness.

37:53.730 --> 37:56.373
Now, do you want to know whether or not you've experienced the grace of God?

37:56.393 --> 37:57.274
It's as simple as this.

37:58.095 --> 38:00.338
Listen, do you believe

38:01.538 --> 38:04.823
that God created you, and therefore he keeps you alive every minute.

38:05.504 --> 38:06.465
You owe him everything.

38:06.505 --> 38:07.807
You owe to live for him.

38:08.208 --> 38:11.352
You owe to put him first in your life, but you don't.

38:11.453 --> 38:13.716
And therefore he deserves to withdraw from you.

38:13.776 --> 38:14.377
You know what that means?

38:14.397 --> 38:15.659
It means you're dead.

38:16.700 --> 38:20.626
If God withdraws from you, which is perfectly logical,

38:21.090 --> 38:29.398
If you've been good to somebody and that person ignores you and is not grateful to you and doesn't trust you and doesn't give you, you're due, you just withdraw from him.

38:29.418 --> 38:34.423
But since God holds us together, it says he holds all the universe together with the word of his power.

38:34.443 --> 38:39.207
He holds your molecules together for him to simply do what is perfectly logical and right.

38:40.108 --> 38:44.032
What, in a sense, what we deserve just to withdraw means that we would fall into nothing.

38:44.733 --> 38:47.756
Do you believe that he has a right to do that?

38:47.796 --> 38:50.258
Do you believe that he owes you death?

38:51.746 --> 38:52.347
Do you believe that?

38:52.547 --> 38:53.568
Ah, you say that's too harsh.

38:53.648 --> 38:59.334
Well, then the idea of God's grace will never, ever turn you into a new person.

38:59.474 --> 39:00.656
It will never amaze you.

39:01.216 --> 39:02.297
It will never shock you.

39:02.738 --> 39:04.480
You probably were never even threatened with it.

39:04.840 --> 39:07.183
And it will never break your heart into eternal softness.

39:09.545 --> 39:10.847
And let me ask you one other question.

39:10.867 --> 39:12.629
So do you believe that God owes you nothing?

39:12.649 --> 39:19.797
Do you believe that you have sinned against him and therefore he does, that he owes you condemnation and death?

39:20.357 --> 39:21.138
Do you believe that?

39:21.250 --> 39:22.252
No, it's too harsh.

39:22.772 --> 39:32.287
You've ruined the whole possibility of having your life absolutely changed the way John Valle Johns was changed by grace, unless you see what he really owes you.

39:32.988 --> 39:35.913
You'll never have your heart broken by what he's given you.

39:35.993 --> 39:49.394
And then secondly, do you believe that Jesus Christ is done the incomprehensible, just like the bishop, that he let you plunder him, that he came to earth and died for you, that he opened his life and poured it out

39:49.570 --> 39:50.331
Do you believe that?

39:50.751 --> 39:51.572
Oh, put it this way.

39:51.932 --> 39:58.299
Do you believe that you are so lost and your sins are so great that only the death of the Son of God could save you?

39:59.720 --> 40:01.142
Ah, you say, well, that's just too harsh.

40:01.222 --> 40:02.063
In that case, fine.

40:02.083 --> 40:03.605
You have a right to your opinion.

40:04.065 --> 40:09.511
You will never have your heart broken into eternal softness by the grace of God.

40:10.512 --> 40:16.658
And that is what happened to John Valjean, as he sang later on in the musical.

40:16.834 --> 40:18.216
My soul belongs to God.

40:18.276 --> 40:19.918
I know I made that bargain long ago.

40:21.180 --> 40:22.942
It was broken, and now he wasn't his own.

40:23.322 --> 40:24.083
And that's what it means.

40:24.184 --> 40:25.345
What does it mean to be a Christian?

40:25.625 --> 40:31.453
To have the grace of God come to you to understand the grace of God, to receive the grace of God, and have it change you forever.

40:31.493 --> 40:33.055
And that's what it means, by the way.

40:33.115 --> 40:34.877
Let's just close up here, dear friends.

40:35.118 --> 40:37.000
Christians, you know what it means to live a life?

40:38.262 --> 40:42.047
Do you know what it means to live a Christian life on the basis of the gospel?

40:42.507 --> 40:44.690
Titus 2.11 says,

40:45.154 --> 40:53.742
For the grace of God that brings salvation teaches us to say no, to all ungodliness and worldly passions, and to live self-controlled upright lives.

40:54.303 --> 40:58.647
That's what it means to take this basics and put it in the middle of your life.

40:58.707 --> 41:00.749
The grace of God teaches you self-control.

41:00.789 --> 41:01.330
Do you hear that?

41:01.930 --> 41:02.651
Let me ask you this.

41:03.312 --> 41:04.833
How do you say no to a temptation?

41:06.875 --> 41:07.536
How do you say no?

41:08.677 --> 41:10.058
How do you argue with yourself?

41:10.078 --> 41:11.500
Do you say God will get me?

41:13.001 --> 41:14.002
People will find out.

41:14.658 --> 41:15.820
I'll hate myself in the morning.

41:16.881 --> 41:18.103
It won't help myself esteem.

41:19.004 --> 41:20.406
I want to be a person of principle.

41:20.486 --> 41:21.247
It's against the law.

41:21.287 --> 41:22.068
I might get caught.

41:22.608 --> 41:23.430
It hurts other people.

41:23.650 --> 41:24.511
It would really look bad.

41:24.932 --> 41:25.913
All of those things are true.

41:26.253 --> 41:29.698
Not one of them will give you self-control.

41:30.439 --> 41:30.739
I know.

41:33.122 --> 41:35.185
The grace of God teaches you to say no.

41:35.606 --> 41:38.369
Just like you go back and say, look what he's done for me.

41:38.690 --> 41:40.272
You let the grace of God argue with you.

41:40.332 --> 41:42.034
It's a rational principle.

41:42.242 --> 41:47.130
It teaches you to say no to all ungodliness and worldly passions and teaches you how to live self-control lives.

41:47.150 --> 41:52.217
Do you know how to let the grace of God come to you again and again and again and again?

41:52.398 --> 41:53.299
It's the only way.

41:54.461 --> 41:55.643
You'll overcome those things.

41:56.083 --> 41:56.905
It's the only way.

41:56.945 --> 42:00.090
Let him argue into courage.

42:01.231 --> 42:02.113
Let him argue you.

42:02.213 --> 42:04.016
Let the grace of God argue you into it.

42:04.416 --> 42:07.100
Let the grace of God come to you again and again and again.

42:07.120 --> 42:08.182
It will teach you.

42:08.262 --> 42:09.364
It will give you self-control.

42:09.684 --> 42:10.706
It'll give you everything.

42:11.906 --> 42:12.427
Let's pray.

42:13.388 --> 42:14.690
Our Father, this is what it means.

42:14.890 --> 42:17.773
We see now to be a Christian, to let the grace of God come.

42:19.155 --> 42:20.036
It starts with you.

42:20.076 --> 42:24.242
You come on in and you show us your grace.

42:24.282 --> 42:26.545
And when we receive your grace, everything is different.

42:26.565 --> 42:27.326
Everything is changed.

42:27.446 --> 42:34.395
I pray, Father, there might be some people here tonight who for the first time realize what it means to let the grace of God come to them.

42:35.616 --> 42:40.242
I pray, Lord, that you will help them to see that being a Christian is not just taking up a set of teachings.

42:41.410 --> 42:49.158
but it's understanding your grace, seeing what you've done, letting the grace of God conquer us.

42:50.680 --> 43:07.638
Would you help, Father, by your Holy Spirit, some people to say tonight, Lord, I see that even though I have lived a life of independence from you, I ask that you would forgive me and receive me as your child, not on the basis of my performance, but on what the basis of what Jesus has done.

43:07.678 --> 43:10.962
And I ask that you'd come into my life to make me

43:11.458 --> 43:15.002
your child, and I want to make you my Lord and Savior.

43:15.062 --> 43:33.483
I don't know, Father, what it will take, how long it will take, but I pray that you would have your spirit hunt down everybody in the hearing of these words with your grace until they are taught how to say no to all on godliness and worldly passions.

43:34.464 --> 43:36.046
Father, that will be perfect freedom.

43:36.967 --> 43:38.449
We ask for it in your son's name.

43:39.310 --> 43:39.730
Amen.

43:45.442 --> 43:49.309
Thanks for listening to today's teaching from Tim Keller here at Gospel and Life.

43:49.910 --> 43:55.940
For the 40 days from Ash Wednesday through Good Friday, Gospel and Life would like to email you a daily lint devotional.

43:56.341 --> 44:00.127
You can sign up to receive these daily emails at gospelandlife.com.

44:00.327 --> 44:02.531
That's gospelandlife.com.

44:03.954 --> 44:06.578
Today's sermon was recorded in 1993.

44:06.754 --> 44:16.306
The sermons and talks you hear on the Gospel and Life podcast were recorded between 1989 and 2017, while Dr. Keller was senior pastor at Redeemer Presbyterian Church.

